Given reluctance of different sub-species to fully mate with each
other, it makes much sense to me. Here's how I see the logic:
First there were one clade of monkeys, then Pangea split, breaking
it into two clades, old world and new world monkeys.
Old world was bigger, so it had room to split further, spawning the
clade of apes from out of the larger clade of monkeys.
Apes were successful and spread between Africa and Borneo.
(I don't know where they started. Do you?)
The African apes were more successful and split further, first
Gorilla / ChiHomid, then Chimp/Homid.
The homids were most successul of them all, inhabiting virtually
all of Africa and spreading small clades outside.
Now here's the key part: Since the home of the homids was Africa,
and it was large enough to support many local populations, and
Africa was hospitable enough to support *large* local populations
almost everywhere, it evolved lots of variation. At first it had
*all* the variation of homids. When a small clade left Africa to
some other continent, *most* of the variation remained in Africa,
so of course with most of the starting points for further
evolution, Africa had the best chances each time to be the lucky
winner with the one new innovation that allowed another sub-clade
to both grow within Africa and expand out of Africa. This one lucky
winner was vastly superior to whatever had left Africa long ago, so
it simply replaced the native populations outside Africa, sometimes
quickly, sometimes it took more time as with Flores man. Within
Africa, because of the many starting points for further evolution,
several clades did almost as well as the *best* clade, able to hold
out against invasion, and persist to this very day. But outside
Africa, with only one starting point, there was no chance to keep
almost up with the latest version of African Windows NT. Each major
round of evolution brought lots of innovations within the surviving
populations in Africa, increasing the variety, until one of them
chanced to get yet another wonderful new innovation that swept its
local part of Africa and also spread unresited through the rest of
the Old world.

It's theoretically possible that just by very good luck the one (1)
small clade in the rest of the Old world might have chanced upon
the one innovation that alllowed them to return back to conquer
part of Africa, but in fact that didn't happen until a few hundred
years ago, and those periods of colonization (Arabs, then
Europeans) were due to advanced technology rather than bare
evolution. For close to a million years, the Africans had the
advantage of more starting points for evolution hence more chance
of the key new innovation, and by chance they held onto that
advantage. Not until agriculture did their dominion end, and not
until advanced technology did anyone else's dominion start.

